%N A270558 Area of the smallest convex n-gon such that all its sides, diagonals and area are distinct integers.
%C A270558 Does such an n-gon exist for all n >= 3? - _Dmitry Kamenetsky_, Feb 15 2017
%H A270558 Carlos Rivera, <a href="http://www.primepuzzles.net/problems/prob_064.htm">Problem 64: prime convex quadrilateral</a>.
%H A270558 Carlos Rivera, <a href="http://www.primepuzzles.net/problems/prob_065.htm">Problem 65: prime convex polygons</a>.
%e A270558 For n=3, we have the triangle with sides 3, 4 and 5. Its area is 6.
%e A270558 For n=4, we have the quadrilateral with sides 10, 17, 28, 35, diagonals 21 and 39, and area 378.
%e A270558 For n=5, we have the 5-gon with sides 21, 41, 175, 140, 85, diagonals 50, 105, 104, 204, 195, and area 9870.
%e A270558 For n=6, we have the 6-gon with sides 47, 663, 264, 169, 105, 1020, diagonals 700, 884, 975, 855, 952, 1001, 425, 520, 272, and area 196950.
%e A270558 For n=7, we have the 7-gon with sides 235, 1320, 1360, 2340, 612, 525, 5100, diagonals 1547, 2805, 4557, 4875, 2600, 4420, 4760, 5005, 3500, 3952, 4301, 2880, 3315, 1131, and area 5695998.
%e A270558 For n=8, we have the 8-gon with sides 1547, 612, 525, 5355, 235, 4275, 845, 1360, diagonals 2125, 2600, 5365, 5304, 2163, 1131, 5520, 5525, 3500, 2805, 5460, 5491, 3952, 3315, 5408, 4301, 3720, 4420, 4875, 4760, and area 12473070.
